==In popular culture==
Belmondo is saluted in a 1967 episode of the U.S. television sitcom ''[[Get Smart]]''. In the episode &quot;The Spirit is Willing&quot; a top agent of the sinister spy agency [[KAOS (Get Smart)|KAOS]] is named Paul John Mondebello, an obvious alteration of Belmondo's name.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/TelevisionCity/3101/3rd.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000312082653/http://www.geocities.com/TelevisionCity/3101/3rd.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 March 2000|title=The Complete Get Smart Guide - Episode Guides: Third Season|date=12 March 2000}}&lt;/ref&gt; He is also mentioned in a song about &quot;Masculinity&quot; in the play ''La Cage Aux Folles''. A poster of him as &quot;A bad guy, a good-looking bad guy&quot; is in Rachel's apartment in &quot;The Light of Day&quot; by Graham Swift. In 1968 a Yugoslavian quartet &quot;[[:hr:Kvartet 4M|Kvartet 4M]]&quot; recorded a song &quot;Bebel&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/4m-Hvala/release/2710040 |title=&quot;4m&quot;* - Hvala (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |accessdate=2017-08-28}}&lt;/ref&gt; about him.

Belmondo's facial features were the inpiration for the character of [[Blueberry_%28comics%29|Blueberry]] in the Franco-Belgian comic book series of the same name by [[Jean-Michel Charlier]] and [[Jean Giraud | Jean &quot;Mœbius&quot; Giraud]].

In the 1966 [[Donovan]] song &quot;Sunny South Kensington&quot;, Belmondo's and [[Mary Quant]]'s drug use is mentioned in the lyric: &quot;Jean-Paul Belmondo and-a Mary Quant got [[wikt:stoned#Adjective|stoned]], to say the least&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Mellow Yellow/Sunny South Kensington 45 rpm single, [[Mellow Yellow]] LP album, side 2, track 5&lt;/ref&gt;

The book [[Youth in Revolt]] by author [[C._D._Payne|C.D. Payne]] and its sequels refer to Belmondo several times and at one point feature the main character going to Mexico and getting plastic surgery in order to resemble Belmondo.

The Manga [[Stardust Crusaders]] features a main character named Jean-Pierre Polnareff, whose first name is a reference to Belmondo.

The Horror-Platformer series [[Castlevania]] Prominently features the Belmont family, which could be a reference to Belmondo, given their Japanese last name is also Belmondo.

In the Netflix series, [[The_Spy_(TV_series)|The Spy]], a bartender is convinced to do a Belmondo impersonation, after being bribed by the Israeli undercover spy, [[Eli Cohen]] (episode 3, &quot;Alone in Damascus&quot;).

The main protagonist in the manga [[Cobra_(manga)#Production|Cobra]], is inspired from Belmondo and his &quot;phlegmatic style&quot;, specifically from his characters on ''[[Breathless_(1960_film)|Breathless]]'' (1960) and ''[[That Man from Rio]]'' (1964).

